    <note>Su(1) Anshi [1489] His ancestors were Wugong jun Su(1). At the end of the Tang, they followed Xizong to Sichuan and became Chengdu residents. His great great grandfather and great grandfather served in the administration of the Meng(2) kings of Shu. After the fall of Shu, his grandfather, Ji [3752], used his father's yin to enter the Song civil service. Both Ji and his son, Xianxi, were buried in Yangzhou, Jiangdu xian in 1057, which had become the Su family burial ground--Anshi was also buried there. Wang Anshi's funerary inscription then says that Su(1) Anshi used the jinshi to establish his family (qijia) branch of the lineage. Anshi was Zhao(1) Yang(1)'s [402] father-in-law. XCB, 157.3a, 181.13b; SHY:ZG, 64.51a-51b; Wang Anshi, WJ, 92.954-955; Yu Jing, WJ, 19.28a, 29a. CBD, 5, 4337.</note>
